d also uses it as a starting point to discuss larger issues of Black Power, the end of empire, British race relations, immigration, and student rights. Coinciding with a student-led campaign against segregated housing, the visit enabled Malcolm X to make connections with radical students from the Caribbean, Africa, and South Asia, giving him a new perspective on the global struggle for racial equality, and in turn, radicalizing a new generation of British activists. Masterfully tracing the reverberations on both sides of the Atlantic, Tuck chronicles how the personal transformation of the dynamic American leader played out on the international stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aAnti-racismzEnglandzOxfordxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack Muslims. 0aCivil rights movementsxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american history.  aafrican americans.  aamerican history.  aamerican racism.  aassassination.  ablack advocacy.  ablack power.  abritish race relations.  abritish students.  acivic.  acivil rights activist.  acivil rights movement.  aempire.  aglobal struggle.  agreat britain.  ahistory.  ahuman rights activist.  aimmigration.  ainequality.  ainternational politics.  ainternational.  amalcolm x.  aoxford.  apolitics.  arace militancy.  aracial equality.  aradical politics.  arevolt.  arevolution.  arevolutionaries.  asegregated housing.  astudent rights.  aunited kingdom.1 aGates, Henry Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027933940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095998940uhttps://ww